    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix CLI prompt behavior and custom prompt handling\n\n### Summary\nThe CLI prompt functionality had several issues that caused incorrect behavior when calling `cli_prompt()`. The main problem was a circular reference where `cli_prompt()` was using `cli_cfg->prompt` to construct the prompt string, but `cli_cfg->prompt` was supposed to contain the final prompt.\n\nAdditionally, the host detection logic was flawed due to an environment variable being set to an empty string, and custom prompts set by users were being overwritten immediately.\n\nThis fix resolves these issues by correcting the prompt generation logic and ensuring proper host detection.\n\n### Changes\n- `openair2/UTIL/CLI/cli.c`: \n  * Fixed `cli_prompt()` function to use `host` variable instead of `cli_cfg->prompt`\n  * Added proper checks for non-empty host environment variables\n  * Removed problematic `putenv(\"REMADDR=\")` line that interfered with host detection\n  * Added fallback to `HOSTNAME` environment variable for better host detection\n\n- `openair2/UTIL/CLI/cli_cmd.c`:\n  * Fixed prompt command to respect custom prompts instead of overwriting them\n  * Added logic to reset to default prompt when empty string is provided\n  * Ensured custom prompts are properly terminated with prompt character\n\n### Reproduction\nBefore this fix, calling the prompt command with a custom value would immediately overwrite it with the default prompt. Additionally, the default prompt would show as \"username@\" instead of \"username@hostname\" because of the circular reference issue.\n\nUsers can reproduce the issue by:\n1. Starting the OAI CLI\n2. Observing that the prompt shows \"username@\" instead of proper hostname\n3. Running \"prompt mycustomprompt\" and observing it gets immediately reset\n"
}